### **Setting up Blender for Character Modelling** 

**IMPORTANT:** Before creating your character model, make sure you setup the unit scale in the scene to avoid scaling issues when importing into Unreal

* Open the .blend file for your model in Blender  
* Navigate to the Scene properties tab   
* Make sure **Unit System** is set to **Metric**   
* Set the **Unit Scale** to **0.01** 

  ![][image1]

* Save the Blender file to keep the changes





  ### **Setting up the Character Rig** 


  Characters, mesh effects, particles (and their animation) are all **authored facing down the** 

  **Z axis**.

  On import, the **Force Front X** axis option is enabled in order to reorient the character down the X axis (facing right in their default gameplay direction).

  Any skeletal structure can be used for imported characters and unreal provides several tools for retargeting within the editor. There is however a basic structure that we try to adhere to for ease of animation sharing and setup.


  #### **Caveats when Importing your Character Model into Unreal** 

* Open your character’s default skin folder in Unreal  
  * **Content/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets/Skins/Default**   
* In the top-left corner of the content drawer, click **Import**

  ![][image2]

* Select the path to the FBX file for the character model you exported from Blender and click **Open**   
  * Ensure **Skeletal Mesh** is checked   
  * Ensure **Import Mesh** is checked   
  * Ensure **Import Animations** is **un**checked   
    ![][image3]  
* Rename your **Skeletal Mesh** asset (the one with the pink line in the thumbnail) to **SK\_\[CharacterPrefix\]\_Default** (replace **\[CharacterPrefix\]** with the first 3 letters of your character’s name)   
  * Keep this file in:  
    * **…/Content/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets/Skins/Default**   
* Rename your **\_PhysicsAsset** file to **HB\_\[CharacterName\]** (replacing **\[CharacterName\]** with your character’s entire name)  
  * Move this file into the base UnrealAssets folder for your mod …/**Content/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets**  
* Rename your **\_Skeleton** file to **SK\_\[CharacterPrefix\]\_Skeleton**   
  * Move this file into …/**Content/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets/Animation**   
    **IMPORTANT:** If your character is imported at too small or too large of a scale, here are a couple of settings you can try one of the following:   
    1\. Adjust the **Unit Scale** from within Blender if you haven’t already:   
* Open the .blend file for your model in Blender.   
* Navigate to the Scene properties tab   
* Make sure **Unit System** is set to **Metric**   
* Set the **Unit Scale** to **0.01** 

   ![][image4]

* Switch to **Object Mode**   
* Select your model’s armature and scale it up to **100**  
* Hit **Ctrl \+ A** and select **All Transforms**   
* Re-export your model and animations from blender, and then reimport them back into Unreal

  2\. Edit the model’s **Import Uniform Scale** in Unreal 

  * Open your **SK\_\[CharacterPrefix\]\_Default** asset (located in **Content/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets/Skins/Default**)  
    * On the right, under the **Asset Details** tab, scroll down until you see **Import Settings**   
      * Expand **Transform**   
      * Set the **Import Uniform Scale** to a different value (for example, you might need to set your scale to **50** if the model is too small). 

    

    #### **Caveats when Importing Animations into Unreal** 

* Open your character’s animation folder in Unreal  
  * **…/Content/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets/Animation**   
* In the top left corner of the content drawer, click **Import**

  ![][image5]

* Select the path to the FBX file containing the animation(s) you exported from Blender and click **Open**   
* Ensure **Import Mesh** is NOT checked (if the FBX also contains your character model) \-   
* Ensure **Import Animations** is checked (if the FBX also contains your character model).   
* **IMPORTANT:** Make sure you set the following values as well. If you don’t, the game will crash when you try to play your character:   
  * Ensure **Use Default Sample Rate** is NOT checked.   
  * Set **Custom Sample Rate** to 60  
    ![][image6]  
      
      
      
    

    ### **Add Animations to Character Data** 

    **IMPORTANT:** The **CharacterData** by default has no animations defined, so you will need to also specify an animation for each state, or else the game will crash if you try to play your character.  
* Open your character’s **CD\_** file located in **Content/ModContent/UnrealAssets**   
* Under the **Animations** category, add an animation to all of the entries under **State Animations**, **Aerial Grabbed Animations**, and **Thrown Animations**.   
  * If you do not have any animations, you can just put a single placeholder animation in each one for now  
  * **Tip:** You can use **Shift \+ Right Mouse Button** to copy an animation in an entry, and then hover over an empty entry and use **Shift \+ Left Mouse Button** to paste the animation   
    * This will help speed up the process of copying the same animation into multiple entries 

    **WARNING:** If you use the above Shift \+ Click shortcuts to copy/paste animations, be sure to save after copying about 10 or so animations

    Sometimes the editor can crash if you copy/paste too quickly using this method, so saving frequently while doing this process will help reduce the risk of losing data and having to start over

      

    

    

    

    

    

    

    ## **Additional Features/Helpful Hints** 

    ### **Character Texture maps** 

    Orms Map: 

    **O**utline (Red Channel): Controls character outline thickness. 

    White \= thicker lines 

    Black \= thinner 

    **R**oughness (Green Channel): Controls how roughness of masked area. **M**etalness (Blue Channel): Controls how a metallic masked area looks. **S**hading (Alpha Channel): Tells the shader how to light the character. 

    CM Map: 

    CM map 1 

    CustomColorX \= Black 

    CustomColor 0 (Red Channel) 

    CustomColor 1 (Green Channel) 

    CustomColor 2 (Blue Channel) 

    CM map 2 

    CustomColor 3 (Red Channel) 

    CustomColor 4 (Green Channel) 

    CustomColor 5 (Blue Channel) 

    CM map 3 

    CustomColor 6 (Red Channel) 

    CustomColor 7 (Green Channel) 

    CustomColor 8 (Blue Channel) 

    Each material can use up to 3 CM maps giving a total of 10 coloring options. 

    Texture Optimization: 

    Try to keep texture sizes under 2048x2048. In most cases 1024x1024 is enough. When exporting your CM mask make sure there is no Alpha channel.

    

    

    

    

    

    

    

    

    ### **Skin Setup** 

1. #### **Create your skin/folder** 

   ○ Head to the Characters folder and open up the character you want to make a skin for (ex.Clairen) 

   ○ Locate and right click the **Char\_Cla** file 

○ Go up to **Scripted Asset Actions** and select **Create New Skin** 

**![][image7]**  
![][image8]

* Fill in the name of the Skin  
  * We’ll use Spotted for the example  
* Select the **default Skin data** file of the character under **Parent Skin.** (ex: Skin\_Cla\_Default)   
* Only check the **Create New Renderer Class** box if the skin involves a new mesh.   
  * Choose the Rarity.   
    * Common: If it’s a recolor   
    * Rare: If it’s a mesh change  
      * We can change this later if need be  
  * **Note:** N**ever** have it set to **Default**, or it will try to set the skin up under the default skin  
  * Lastly: do not touch the **Is Excluded from Build** checkbox,   
    * Should be checked by default

    


      #### **2\. Adding your files to the folder**

    ![][image9]

    This Folder should contain the Data folder, your Skin’s Materials, and all the Texture Maps (N if needed, ORMS if needed, and the CMs) 

* Drag in your texture files and head over to the default skins folder and copy and paste the materials you need to add your textures to.   
* Right-click your materials, go to the Scripted Actions and hit **Rename Multiple Files**.   
* Have it replace, in this example, Default with Spotted.   
* Open up your ORMS and CM maps and set their **Compression Settings** to **Masks (no sRGB)**   
* Also if that mask doesn’t have anything in the alpha channel check the **Compress Without Alpha** checkbox


  ![][image10]


![][image11]

![][image12]

![][image13]

* Now add your maps into their respective materials and check that the masks are working as intended  
* You can go to the default skin folder and pull out the **Clairen BP** into the scene and add your materials to that mesh to help visualize what the masks are doing. If everything checks out and your masks are working correctly, apply the new materials to the **default neutral CS file**   
  * Located in the Data\>Palettes\>Neutral\>first file on the left   
  * When applying materials to a CS file you only have to do it in the **Neutral** one, the others(red, blue, green) will inherit any changes made to it   
  * You only need to make new materials if you have new masks you want to use, otherwise we can use the original masks to customize those areas on the skin  
      
      
      
      
    While we're here, let’s explain a couple important parts of the CS file:  
* When you make a skin your PS file should populate in the **Skin Color Palette** section   
* If you were working on a **Palette** for the Default skin, there would be **no file** in the Skin Color Palette section; instead the PS file you are working on would be in the **Base Color Palette** section  
* If you are working on a palette for a skin however, that PS file would be in the **Skin Color Palette** because you are working on a skin, not the base  
* The **Elemental Palette** section is for when you need to customize a **PE file**   
* PE files are where we customize the colors of a character's elements/vfx   
* Lastly, we have the section for the **Character Select Portrait**. It should have an empty file in there at the moment, but when we go to create the CSP in the photobooth it will auto-update here


  


  


  


  


  


  


  


  


  


  


  


  


  


  #### **3\. Create your Color Definitions** 

  **![][image14]**

  Color Definitions(Skin Data): 

* Open up the Skin Data file for your skin and head over to the **Colors** section  
* If you open up the **Base Material Slots** section you’ll see all of the characters original materials and Color slots that have been created to customize the colors  
* You will need to go to the **Skin Material Slots** and update those to be able to customize your skin  
  * Hit the **\+** to add a material. (e.g. Body)   
  * Open the Material Parameters and add a color slot  
    * Example: CustomColor0 and name it with whatever that mask is in charge of customizing. Refer to your handy notepad with all your Custom colors and their names  
* If you want to be able to customize other materials on the character, but didn’t create new masks, create a material slot with the same name as the original material and copy and paste its color slots over  
  * The way the system works is if a skin has a color slot for an original material it will override and allow you to customize those materials on the new skin   
  * **Pro Tip:** If two color slots share the same name they will share the same color selection   
    * This used to be useful when we wanted fewer color options, but leaving all the slots open to be independently customized is more desired  
    * Once you have created all the material slots you want with all of their color slots, hit compile and get ready to transfer these definitions to the CS files 

  #### **4\. Transfer your color definitions** 

* Go to the palettes folder and type CS into the search **![][image15]**  
* Select the first four CS files on the left, right-click the selection, click Scripted Asset Actions,  and choose **Import Custom Color Assignments**   
* Type in the name of your skin and select your skin data file

![][image16]

* You have now added your color slots to your PS files and can begin customizing your colors   
* Head to the photobooth and start picking colors   
  * You can head up to the **How to make a Palette section** to get a refresher on the photobooth

    

    

    

    

    

    

    

  


  #### **5\. Fill in colors in the photobooth** 

* Head to the **Photobooth Level** to start customizing your colors  
  * Click the camera to use the tool   
  * On the right, under **Custom Color Viewer**, choose the skin and color slot you want to customize and hit **Load Skin and Color Slot**   
  * Hit **G** to hide the camera, so we can focus on the skin  
    * If you accidentally click off the tool, navigate to the top-right and click **BP\_RivalCapture**  
* If done right, we should be looking like this  
  * Image: a blank character waiting to have their colors selected  
* **Pro Tip:** You can copy the colors over from the default palette and then slide over to the colors you think fit the palette best.   
  * This will help you stay within the range of values that the skin has  
* Once you’re done making your choices click BOTH:  
  * **Save SkinCustomColor**   
  * **Save ElementalCustomColorSlot**  
* Scroll up to the **CSS Portrait Tool** and click either **Generate CSS Portraits for Displayed Skin** or **Save CSS Portraits for Current Palette**   
  * Which you select depends on whether you want to print the CSP of what you’re working on, or if you want to take a fresh set of CSP’s of the skin line  
      
      
      
      
  


    #### **6\. Check in-game** 

* Go to the **Editor Preferences**  
* Click **Rivals Developer Settings** select your skin and the color you want to check   
* You can add up to 4 colors to view at once in this menu

  **![][image17]**

   ![][image18]

* Load up the **DebugRoom** level and boot the game  
* After some compiling you should see your skin loaded up in-game  
  * Take this time to check if the colors look cohesive and have similar values  
    * It’s best to navigate the menus with a controller   
  * If you’re on keyboard, press F8 to navigate through the window with Unreal controls

If nothing blows up and you’re satisfied with your colors, you have completed a Common Skin\!
